Here's the complete migration from ASP.NET WebForms to ASP.NET Core (.NET 8).

## Pattern Inventory

Your code has **two** Thread.Abort patterns:

| Location | API | Pattern |
|---|---|---|
| `btnExport_Click` | `Response.End()` | ASP.NET request termination |
| `btnRedirect_Click` | `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | ASP.NET request termination |
| `btnRedirect_Click` | `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | ThreadAbortException as control flow |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using System.Text;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // Return a FileResult — the framework handles the response lifecycle.
        // No Response.End() needed; returning ends request processing.
        return File(
            Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv");
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Redirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Redirect() without endResponse — returning the result
            // ends request processing cooperatively.
            return RedirectToAction("Index", "Login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No ThreadAbortException catch — it doesn't exist in .NET 8.
        // OperationCanceledException replaces it if you need
        // cancellation-aware error handling.
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Client disconnected mid-request — log and bail out.
            return StatusCode(499); // Client Closed Request
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

### 1. `Response.End()` → return `IActionResult`
ASP.NET Core has no `Response.End()`. Returning from the action method **is** ending the response. `File(...)` sets headers and streams the body — no manual `Response.Clear()`, `AddHeader()`, or `Write()` needed.

### 2. `Response.Redirect(url, true)` → return `Redirect(url)`
The `true` (endResponse) parameter existed to call `Thread.Abort` and prevent code after the redirect from running. In ASP.NET Core, `return Redirect(...)` naturally stops execution — no abort mechanism needed.

### 3. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` → removed
This catch block only existed to swallow the exception that `Response.Redirect(url, true)` threw internally. Since the redirect no longer throws, the catch is unnecessary. If you need to detect **client disconnection**, catch `OperationCanceledException` and check `HttpContext.RequestAborted`:

```csharp
catch (OperationCanceledException) when (HttpContext.RequestAborted.IsCancellationRequested)
{
    // Client disconnected — clean up
}
```

### 4. `User.Identity.IsAuthenticated` → null-safe check
In ASP.NET Core, `User.Identity` can be `null` when no auth middleware has run.

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Impact |
|---|---|
| Writing to `Response.Body` after returning an `IActionResult` | Throws `InvalidOperationException` — response already started |
| Calling `Response.Redirect()` on `HttpResponse` directly without returning | Code continues executing past the redirect (no abort to stop it!) |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` and swallowing it | Masks client disconnections; let it propagate or handle explicitly |
| Missing `[Authorize]` attribute | The manual `IsAuthenticated` check works but the middleware approach is idiomatic in Core |

## Bonus: Idiomatic Version with Auth Middleware

```csharp
[Authorize] // Handles unauthenticated → /login redirect via config
public class ReportController : Controller
{
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        // Pass cancellationToken to long-running work
        var data = GenerateReport(cancellationToken);
        return File(Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data), "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Process()
    {
        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

ASP.NET Core automatically binds `CancellationToken` parameters to `HttpContext.RequestAborted`, giving you cooperative cancellation for free.
